.Im MicroEmacs variable;environment
.so me.tni
.TH $search-path 5
.XI $search-path - "MicroEmacs search path"
.XI $MEPATH - "MicroEmacs search path"
.SH NAME
.Me "|$seach-path"
$search-path \- MicroEmacs search path
.Me "|$MEPATH"
$MEPATH \- MicroEmacs search path
.Me $a
.SH SYNOPSIS
.na
.B $search-path
.I string
.sp
.I "[Microsoft Windows/MS-DOS]"
.br
.B MEPATH=
\fI<path1>\fR\|\fB;\fR\|\fI<path2>\fR\fB;\fR....\fB;\fR\|\fI<pathn>\fR
.sp
.I "[UNIX]"
.br
.B MEPATH=
\fI<path1>\fR\|\fB:\fR\|\fI<path2>\fR\fB:\fR....\fB:\fR\|\fI<pathn>\fR
.ad
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B $search-path
is initialized to the environment variable
.BR $MEPATH ,
and  identifies the search paths which are searched to locate editor  specific
files. Multiple search paths may be specified,  separated by the platform path
separator  (semi-colon  ('\fB;\fR')  on  Microsoft  Windows  or  \s-1MS-DOS\s0
environments  and a colon  ('\fB:\fR')  on  \s-1UNIX\s0  environments).  Where
multiple search paths are defined then they are search left to right.
.PP
The search  paths are  generally  ordered  from  highest  priority  to lowest
priority and might be arranged such as:-
.IP
\fBMEPATH=\fR\|\fI<user>\fR:\fI<company>\fR:\fI<me>\fR
.LP
where \fI<user>\fR  represents the users path;  \fI<company>\fR is the company
file path (e.g. template files) and \fI<me>\fR are the standard \*(mE files.
.PP
This would correspond to a directory installation, of user \fBfoo\fR such as:-
.CS
/usr/foo/microemacs   - User files.
/usr/group/microemacs - Company wide files
/usr/local/microemacs - MicroEmacs installation directory
.CE
and a \fB$MEPATH\fR such as:-
.CS
MEPATH=/usr/foo/microemacs:/usr/group/microemacs:/usr/local/microemacs
.CE 0
.SH USAGE
The current working directory is checked first for the location of a file.
.PP
.B $search-path
is used to locate all macro files, and other files located with operators such
as
.Ht &find 4 .
.SH NOTES
If  \fB$MEPATH\fR  is not set then  \fB$search-path\fR  is  initialized to the
environment variable \fB$PATH\fR.
.PP
On \s-1UNIX\s0 systems the path  \fI/usr/local/microemacs\fR  is automatically
added to the end of  \fB$MEPATH\fR,  or if not  defined, to the  beginning  of
\fB$PATH\fR.
